  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In this letter, Lucia Weston wrote: &quot;Wendell made his &apos;maiden speech&apos; it was I heard a very fine one.&quot; Henry B. Stanton and Wendell Phillips planned that the latter should speak before the legislature. The box from the ladies of Darlington, England, arrived with a letter from George Thompson. Lucia relates that &quot;about one thousand mobbers&quot; were gathered when Gershaw(?) lectured to the Ladies [Anti-Slavery Society?], and &quot;every lady that came out was hissed.&quot; Mrs. [Thankful Hussey] Southwick &quot;was on the spot and addressed several of the men.&quot; Lucia and Caroline Weston went to the Smith school house to help teach in the colored school.</subfield>
  </datafield>
